{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3491257,"name":"Saahil Farook","username":"saahilsterr","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/s/67e7ee/{size}.png","created_at":"2025-01-24T01:00:00.019Z","cooked":"<p>I’m having issues with the accuracy of my Motion Magic. I’m reporting rotations and it’s +/- 0.03 originally. When I try moving it 2 rotations and then back to 0 the error increases. How do I make it where it always reaches back to 0 no matter how much times I use it?<br>
. Here is the code I used below:</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">// Copyright (c) FIRST and other WPILib contributors.
// Open Source Software; you can modify and/or share it under the terms of
// the WPILib BSD license file in the root directory of this project.

package frc.robot.subsystems;

import static edu.wpi.first.units.Units.Degree;
import static edu.wpi.first.units.Units.Degrees;
import static edu.wpi.first.units.Units.Rotations;
import static edu.wpi.first.units.Units.Seconds;
import static edu.wpi.first.units.Units.Volts;

import com.ctre.phoenix6.SignalLogger;
import com.ctre.phoenix6.configs.TalonFXConfiguration;
import com.ctre.phoenix6.controls.MotionMagicVoltage;
import com.ctre.phoenix6.controls.VoltageOut;
import com.ctre.phoenix6.hardware.TalonFX;

import edu.wpi.first.math.MathUtil;
import edu.wpi.first.units.AngleUnit;
import edu.wpi.first.units.measure.Angle;
import edu.wpi.first.wpilibj.smartdashboard.SmartDashboard;
import edu.wpi.first.wpilibj2.command.Command;
import edu.wpi.first.wpilibj2.command.SubsystemBase;
import edu.wpi.first.wpilibj2.command.sysid.SysIdRoutine;

public class TestSub extends SubsystemBase {
  /** Creates a new TestSub. */
  TalonFX motor = new TalonFX(14);
  private MotionMagicVoltage mmRequest = new MotionMagicVoltage(0);

  private VoltageOut vOut = new VoltageOut(0.0);

  private final SysIdRoutine sysRoutine = new SysIdRoutine(
      new SysIdRoutine.Config(
          null,
          Volts.of(7),
          Seconds.of(3),
          state -&gt; SignalLogger.writeString("state", state.toString())),
      new SysIdRoutine.Mechanism(
          volts -&gt; motor.setControl(vOut.withOutput(volts.in(Volts))),
          null,
          this));

  public Command sysIDQuasistatic(SysIdRoutine.Direction direction) {
    return sysRoutine.quasistatic(direction);
  }

  public Command sysIDDynamic(SysIdRoutine.Direction direction) {
    return sysRoutine.dynamic(direction);
  }

  public TestSub() {
    MotorConfig();
  }

  private void MotorConfig() {
    var wristConfig = new TalonFXConfiguration();
    wristConfig.Feedback.SensorToMechanismRatio = 25;

    var slot0Config = wristConfig.Slot0;
    slot0Config.kS = 0.10442;
    slot0Config.kV = 0.10882;
    slot0Config.kA = 0.001647;
    slot0Config.kP = 0.02;
    slot0Config.kI = 0;
    slot0Config.kD = 0.01;

    var wristMotionMagic = wristConfig.MotionMagic;
    wristMotionMagic.MotionMagicCruiseVelocity = 1000;
    wristMotionMagic.MotionMagicAcceleration = 200;
    wristMotionMagic.MotionMagicJerk = 10;

    motor.getConfigurator().apply(wristConfig);
  }

  public void Move(double speed) {
    motor.set(speed * 0.25);
    System.out.println(MotorAngle());
  }

  public void MagicMove(double degrees) {
    // double toDegrees = degrees / 360;
    // double processed = toDegrees * 25;

    motor.setControl(mmRequest.withPosition(degrees * 25));
    System.out.println(MotorAngle());
  }

  private double MotorAngle() {
    return motor.getPosition().getValue().in(Rotations);
  }

  @Override
  public void periodic() {
    // This method will be called once per scheduler run
    SmartDashboard.putNumber("degrees", MotorAngle());
  }
}

</code></pre>","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"posts_count":5,"updated_at":"2025-01-24T01:14:05.268Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":573,"reads":222,"readers_count":221,"score":2909.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":483319,"topic_slug":"motion-magic-help-ctre","display_username":"Saahil Farook","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":2,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":67109,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/motion-magic-help-ctre/483319/1","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true,"can_vote":false},{"id":3491309,"name":"Benjamin Hall","username":"bhall-ctre","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/bhall-ctre/{size}/198180_2.png","created_at":"2025-01-24T02:04:19.865Z","cooked":"<p>Firstly, everything on the Talon FX operates in terms of mechanism rotations, not rotor degrees. That means that if MagicMove takes degrees right now, you need to convert that to rotations (divide by 360.0), or otherwise just take rotations. Additionally, if you set the SensorToMechanismRatio (which you currently do), you don’t need to multiply your input to MotionMagic by your gear ratio, as we expect mechanism rotations (after the SensorToMechanismRatio).</p>
<p>Given that, your Motion Magic configs and <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> gains are also off from what they should be. For Motion Magic configs, the max possible cruise velocity for a Kraken X60 is <code>100.0 / sensor to mech ratio</code>. So I would probably set your cruise velocity to 3.5 mechanism RPS (~90.0 rps / 25.0) to give yourself some headroom.</p>
<p>From there, acceleration depends on how long you want the profile to take to reach max velocity. If you want it to take about half a second, then acceleration should be double your cruise velocity. For 0.2 s, it should be 5x your cruise velocity.</p>
<p>Jerk is optional, but if you want to include it for smoother motion, a good starting point is around 10x your acceleration, which means the acceleration would take 0.1 s to reach the max.</p>
<p>As for your <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> gains, your kS is fine, but your other gains are going to be far too weak in terms of mechanism rotations. For a SensorToMechanismRatio of 25, I would expect a kV of 2.75 and a kP of around 50-100 for reference. You can use SysId to find your gains, otherwise you can manually tune them. If you use SysId, make sure your SensorToMechanismRatio is applied before you run the test.</p>","post_number":2,"post_type":1,"posts_count":5,"updated_at":"2025-01-24T02:07:47.697Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":11,"reads":194,"readers_count":193,"score":143.8,"yours":false,"topic_id":483319,"topic_slug":"motion-magic-help-ctre","display_username":"Benjamin Hall","primary_group_name":"CTRE","flair_name":"CTRE","flair_url":"/uploads/default/original/3X/1/b/1bd2b430e1bb6427d1c6504ff6abcd31de851a6d.png","flair_bg_color":"","flair_color":"","flair_group_id":57,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":3}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":48146,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"Software Engineering Intern at CTR Electronics"},"post_url":"/t/motion-magic-help-ctre/483319/2","custom_user_title":"Software Engineering Intern at CTR Electronics","reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":3}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":3,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":3491314,"name":"Saahil Farook","username":"saahilsterr","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/s/67e7ee/{size}.png","created_at":"2025-01-24T02:12:35.198Z","cooked":"<p>Thank you for the input. I didn’t use sensor to mechanism ratio because I’m not using an external encoder, thus why I multplied by the gear ratio instead. Additionally, Those values I’ve recieved are from SysID. The reason (atleast what I think) why it’s so low is because the motor is free spinning. As you mentioned the max cruise velocity is there a way to do it without SensorToMechRatio? Everytime I turn off and turn on the robot it resets the rotations to 0. After continuos cycling between different set points the error rate gets higher.</p>","post_number":3,"post_type":1,"posts_count":5,"updated_at":"2025-01-24T02:12:35.198Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":2,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":7,"reads":171,"readers_count":170,"score":74.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":483319,"topic_slug":"motion-magic-help-ctre","display_username":"Saahil Farook","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":48146,"username":"bhall-ctre","name":"Benjamin Hall","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/bhall-ctre/{size}/198180_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":67109,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/motion-magic-help-ctre/483319/3","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":3491323,"name":"Benjamin Hall","username":"bhall-ctre","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/bhall-ctre/{size}/198180_2.png","created_at":"2025-01-24T02:22:26.081Z","cooked":"<aside class="quote no-group" data-username="saahilsterr" data-post="3" data-topic="483319">
<div class="title">
<div class="quote-controls"></div>
<img loading="lazy" alt="" width="24" height="24" src="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/s/67e7ee/48.png" class="avatar"> saahilsterr:</div>
<blockquote>
<p>I didn’t use sensor to mechanism ratio because I’m not using an external encoder, thus why I multplied by the gear ratio instead.</p>
</blockquote>
</aside>
<p>You’re setting the SensorToMechanismRatio in this line:</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">    wristConfig.Feedback.SensorToMechanismRatio = 25;
</code></pre>
<p>This does work and is a recommended way to account for the gear ratio on the system. The SensorToMechanismRatio applies even when not using an external encoder; for an external encoder 1:1 with the mechanism, you would typically use the RotorToSensorRatio instead.</p>
<aside class="quote no-group" data-username="saahilsterr" data-post="3" data-topic="483319">
<div class="title">
<div class="quote-controls"></div>
<img loading="lazy" alt="" width="24" height="24" src="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/s/67e7ee/48.png" class="avatar"> saahilsterr:</div>
<blockquote>
<p>Additionally, Those values I’ve recieved are from SysID.</p>
</blockquote>
</aside>
<p>Those look like the values SysId would report prior to setting <code>SensorToMechanismRatio = 25</code>, so I would recommend re-running the test with that config applied. SensorToMechanismRatio impacts the reported position/velocity and, as a result, the gains calculated by SysId.</p>
<aside class="quote no-group" data-username="saahilsterr" data-post="3" data-topic="483319">
<div class="title">
<div class="quote-controls"></div>
<img loading="lazy" alt="" width="24" height="24" src="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/s/67e7ee/48.png" class="avatar"> saahilsterr:</div>
<blockquote>
<p>the motor is free spinning</p>
</blockquote>
</aside>
<p>That would also result in lower values, the values you have are close to what I would expect for SensorToMechanismRatio = 1 and a free-spinning motor. With that said, under the “Feedback Analysis” portion, make sure you select the “<span class="abbreviation">CTRE<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Cross The Road Electronics"></template></span> Phoenix 6” preset, as doing so can give you stronger kP and kD gains thanks to the faster onboard <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span>.</p>
<aside class="quote no-group" data-username="saahilsterr" data-post="3" data-topic="483319">
<div class="title">
<div class="quote-controls"></div>
<img loading="lazy" alt="" width="24" height="24" src="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/s/67e7ee/48.png" class="avatar"> saahilsterr:</div>
<blockquote>
<p>Everytime I turn off and turn on the robot it resets the rotations to 0. After continuos cycling between different set points the error rate gets higher.</p>
</blockquote>
</aside>
<p>For the reboot issue, the only way around that is to either have an absolute encoder on the system (which is easy for an arm but not something like an elevator), or have a zeroing procedure, such as using limit switches to reset the position. As for the general error while driving the motor, I believe that just comes down to the <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> gains being too weak to close the loop on the error with your current configs.</p>","post_number":4,"post_type":1,"posts_count":5,"updated_at":"2025-01-24T02:25:49.190Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":3,"quote_count":1,"incoming_link_count":66,"reads":160,"readers_count":159,"score":382.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":483319,"topic_slug":"motion-magic-help-ctre","display_username":"Benjamin Hall","primary_group_name":"CTRE","flair_name":"CTRE","flair_url":"/uploads/default/original/3X/1/b/1bd2b430e1bb6427d1c6504ff6abcd31de851a6d.png","flair_bg_color":"","flair_color":"","flair_group_id":57,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":1}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":48146,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"Software Engineering Intern at CTR Electronics"},"post_url":"/t/motion-magic-help-ctre/483319/4","custom_user_title":"Software Engineering Intern at CTR Electronics","reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":1}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":1,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":true,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":3491980,"name":"Saahil Farook","username":"saahilsterr","avatar_te